08269nam a22009615i 9781442670921DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182006onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426709217 a10.3138/97814426709212doi  a(DE-B1597)497034  a(OCoLC)1076414793  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aK2146b.A93 2006eb 7aPOL0090002bisacsh04a347/.01400aAppointing Judges in an Age of Judicial Power :bCritical Perspectives from around the World /ced. by Kate Malleson, Peter H. Russell. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (450 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tPART ONE: Appointing Judges in Established Democracies -- t1. The Scottish Judicial Appointments Board: New Wine in Old Bottles? -- t2. The New Judicial Appointments Commission in England and Wales: New Wine in New Bottles? -- t3. Judicial Appointments in Post-Charter Canada: A System in Transition -- t4. Legal Controversies over Federal Judicial Selection in the United States: Breaking the Cycle of Obstruction and Retribution over Judicial Appointments -- t5. Judicial Appointments in New Zealand: If it were done when ’tis done, then ’twere well it were done openly and directly -- t6. ‘The judicial whisper goes around’: Appointment of Judicial Officers in Australia -- t7. Merit Selection and Diversity in the Dutch Judiciary -- t8. Judicial Selection in Italy: A Civil Service Model with Partisan Results -- t9. The Selection of Judges in France: Searching for a New Legitimacy -- t10. The Selection Process of Constitutional Court Judges in Germany -- tPART TWO: Appointing the Judges of International Courts -- t11. Judicial Selection for International Courts: Towards Common Principles and Practices -- tPART THREE: Appointing Judges in New Democracies and Transitional States -- t12. Judicial Appointments and Promotions in Israel: Constitution, Law and Politics -- t13. The Politics of Judicial Selection in Egypt -- t14. Judicial Selection in Post-Apartheid South Africa -- t15. A Judiciary in Transition: Reflections on the Selection of Judges in Namibia -- t16. Creating a Compliant Judiciary in Zimbabwe, 2000–2003 -- t17. The Politics of Judicial Selection and Appointments in Japan and Ten South and Southeast Asian Countries -- t18. Judicial Selection in Russia: Towards Accountability and Centralization -- t19. Improving the Quality of the Judiciary in China: Recent Reforms to the Procedures for Appointing, Promoting, and Discharging Judges -- tConclusion -- tTable of Cases -- tBibliography -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe global expansion in judicial power has led to a growing interest in the way judges are chosen. Reform of the judicial selection process is on the political agenda in many countries but the nature of that process differs according to the type of process used - whether a career judiciary, an elected judiciary (direct and indirect), appointment by the executive, or a hybrid system.The main aim of this volume is to analyse common issues arising from increasing judicial power in the context of different political and legal systems, including those in North America, Africa, Europe, Australia, and Asia. The contributors seek to assess the strengths and weaknesses of structural and procedural reforms being proposed or implemented. Particularly important issues include the growing pressure to rethink the balance between judicial independence and accountability and the growing recognition of the importance of selecting judiciaries with a greater diversity in composition. Edited by Kate Malleson and Peter H. Russell, the volume marks the first time an analysis of judicial selection in such a wide range of different systems has been undertaken. It will 